ğŸ”¹ 2. Pixels & Intensity Values (Detailed)
2.1 Pixel

A pixel (picture element) is the smallest unit of a digital image.

Pixel Depth / Bit Depth

Defines how many intensity levels a pixel can store.

Bit Depth	Levels	Range
1-bit	2	0â€“1
8-bit	256	0â€“255
16-bit	65,536	0â€“65535
24-bit RGB	16.7M	(3 Ã— 8-bit)

Higher bit depth â†’ smoother color transitions.

2.2 Intensity

Intensity = brightness.

Grayscale â†’ single intensity

Color â†’ 3 intensity values (R,G,B)

Linear vs Nonlinear Intensity

Displays use gamma correction

Human eye is nonlinear â†’ more sensitive to dark changes than bright

ğŸ”¹ 3. Image Histogram (In Depth)

An image histogram shows how many pixels exist at each intensity value.

3.1 Histogram for Grayscale

X-axis â†’ intensity (0â€“255)

Y-axis â†’ pixel count

What histograms tell you

Dark image â†’ peaks near 0

Bright image â†’ peaks near 255

High contrast â†’ values spread out

Low contrast â†’ values clustered

3.2 Histogram for Color Images

Separate histograms:

Red channel histogram

Green channel histogram

Blue channel histogram

Useful in:

Contrast enhancement

Thresholding

Segmentation

Equalization

