5.2 Quantization

Quantization = converting continuous intensity â†’ discrete levels.

Example:

8-bit image: 256 levels

2-bit image: only 4 levels

Higher quantization â†’ smoother gradients
Lower â†’ posterization (banding effect)

ğŸ”¹ 6. Color Spaces (Very Deep Explanation)

Color spaces are mathematical models that describe how colors are represented.

ğŸŸ© 6.1 RGB Color Space

RGB = Red, Green, Blue

Additive color model

Used in screens, cameras

Values: 0â€“255 for each channel

Pros:

Simple

Standard for devices

Cons:

R, G, B channels are correlated

Sensitive to lighting

Not ideal for segmentation

ğŸŸ¦ 6.2 HSV Color Space

HSV = Hue, Saturation, Value

Components:

Hue â†’ color type

Saturation â†’ purity of color

Value â†’ brightness

Why HSV is important?

Color detection is easy

Lighting has less effect

Skin detection

Masking and segmentation

Example:
To detect yellow color â†’ threshold on Hue only.

ğŸŸ§ 6.3 LAB Color Space

LAB = Lightness, a*, b*

Components:

L â†’ lightness

a â†’ green â†” red

b â†’ blue â†” yellow

Why LAB is used?

Closest to human vision

Good for:

Color correction

White balancing

Histogram equalization

Used in Photoshop and industrial applications.

ğŸŸ« 6.4 YCbCr Color Space

Used in:

JPEG compression

Videos

TV broadcasting

Components:

Y â†’ luminance (brightness)

Cb â†’ blue chroma

Cr â†’ red chroma

Why use YCbCr?

Separating lightness and color improves compression

Human eyes are less sensitive to color than brightness
